`crates/steno` is a compiler crate turning `.steno` dictionary source into Plover dictionary text and LSP snippet bodies, plus a Neovim-integration and keystroke-simulation layer used to validate rendered output. Consumers depend on `lib.rs`'s public API (`expand_dict`, `build_plain_dict`/`build_smart_dict`, snippet builders); the crate never does file I/O itself, and never panics on malformed input — every stage returns one of the typed errors in `error.rs`.

The internal pipeline is a strict producer/consumer chain (parse → expand → render/snippet), with `editor::Behaviors` (`PLAIN`/`SMART`) as a shared constant both `render/` and `blocks.rs` must stay in sync with — editing one without the other silently changes auto-indent emission. `stroke/` is the other cross-cutting dependency, underlying count arithmetic in `expand/` and stroke text formatting in `render/`/`snippet/`; its canonical ordering is not preserved from source, only re-derived.

The test suite is the executable spec for this contract and is unusually load-bearing: most integration tests load the real root-level `dict.steno` and hardcode specific strokes/counts/corpus-size thresholds against it, so editing that dictionary can break many tests at once with no single owner of corpus compatibility. Two files (`smart.rs`, `snippet.rs`) hand-construct synthetic `TypedEntry`/`Entry` values to cover cases the corpus no longer exercises — any change to those types' field sets must be reflected in both synthesized paths. `cpp_check.rs`/`infinite.rs` pin the walker against independent oracles (a C++ reference impl and `expand_dict` itself), and `nvim_plugin.rs`/`snippet.rs` share sentinel constants that must move together.

No intent.md exists at the crate root, `src/`, or `tests/`, so no divergence can be assessed.